B602850CD6764DD3B7224CC53E58466C.description:
evaluating the legacy of Dr. Martin Luther King, Jr., including "A Letter from a
Birmingham Jail,” civil disobedience, the Southern Christian Leadership Conference,
the “I Have a Dream” speech, and his assassination;

CD5081B8F7E147669008AB923FA24706.description:
evaluating and explaining the impact of the Brown v. Board of Education decision and Virginia’s response of Massive Resistance, including, but not limited to the roles of
Barbara Johns, R.R. Moton High School in Prince Edward County, Thurgood Marshall,
and Oliver W. Hill, Sr;

6B284E5E0001471C84A261D6931803AB.description:
explaining the origins and early development of the Cold War and how it changed
American foreign policy, including, but not limited to the Truman Doctrine and the
policy of containment;

8702B9467822457CBB8D499C1CD93B7C.description:
explaining American military intelligence and technology, including island hopping, the
Manhattan Project, and the bombings of the Japanese cities of Hiroshima and Nagasaki;
and

C426750B314C430A8EEF6D96859D9514.description:
evaluating and explaining the contributions of heroic military units including, but not
limited to segregated, minority units, women, and the role of Virginia units in the America
war effort;

78B8F4D8DFCB420B800B8CC6F2261EC1.description:
analyzing the causes and events that led to America’s involvement, including the attack on
Pearl Harbor, the U.S. response with Executive Order 9066 and the incarceration of
Japanese Americans, and the Supreme Court case Korematsu v. United States;

BCC5086F5AC644469A951858A12E858C.description:
analyzing the Roaring 20s, post-wartime effects on the American economy, how
life changed as a result of innovation and inventions, and the diffusion of
American popular culture;

848C8FF8347A499AB77603C5B12BADE0.description:
examining the purposes of Marcus Garvey’s “Back-to-Africa” movement, the
American Civil Liberties Union, the National Association for the Advancement of
Colored People, and the Anti-Defamation League;

AE3EABA23C314D55A26C40708B163937.description:
analyzing the attacks on civil liberties, including, but not limited to the reemergence of the Ku Klux Klan, the Chicago riot of 1919, the Tulsa Race
Massacre and the decimation of Black Wall Street, and the institution of redlining
and resulting racial wealth gaps;

92ECFD9BA8AD422B8E49802AF1D2CECD.description:
evaluating the United States’ involvement in World War I, including, but not limited to
Woodrow Wilson’s Fourteen Points and the establishment of the League of Nations;
and

0467F040FFBE481FB0FAB2D10EF9EB96.description:
explaining the international significance of U.S. decisions and actions, including, but
not limited to the Roosevelt Corollary to the Monroe Doctrine, the Spanish-American
War, the acquisition of Alaska and Hawaii, and the Panama Canal construction;

E3BA20D880E44F13B7340FA8292718BD.description:
explaining changes in foreign policy of the United States toward Latin America and
Asia and the growing influence of the United States, including, but not limited to the
impact of the Spanish-American War;

B073CD71DAB34BA29B863AFB92C611D4.description:
evaluating and explaining the Progressive Movement and the impact of its
legislation, including, but not limited to regulations for pollution, child labor, and
food safety;

A0F328DDED4D44D0AA19B0F0E75FDFD0.description:
explaining the social and cultural impact of industrialization, including, but not
limited to rapid urbanization, the effects on living and working conditions, the
development of labor unions, and the emergence of more leisure time and activities;

3EF064F0F5524121A589D2E2BE84D98A.description:
analyzing the effects of westward movement and the admission of new states on the
Indigenous peoples and the conflicts with the U.S. government, including, but not
limited to the Battle of Little Bighorn and Wounded Knee;

BAB702EF3D794BB783F1315D660966B7.description:
evaluating and explaining the significance and development of Abraham Lincoln’s
leadership and political statements, including, but not limited to the significance of the
Emancipation Proclamation and the principles outlined in the Gettysburg Address;

F3BFCA912B09465E92DE7E9EDB02F3DF.description:
describing major events and the roles of key leaders of the Civil War Era, including, but
not limited to Abraham Lincoln, Jefferson Davis, Ulysses S. Grant, Robert E. Lee, and
Frederick Douglass;

26EBD3B57B944F8B9E6B6B526E425AA7.description:
analyzing the United States' subsequent actions with respect to its Indigenous
peoples, including, but not limited to the Indian Reorganization Acts and McGirt v.
Oklahoma;

569FCA7DC0BE4562A9EC335662A11DD9.description:
explaining the influence and achievements of significant leaders of the time,
including, but not limited to John Marshall, Andrew Jackson, Chief Tecumseh, Chief
Logan, Chief John Ross, and Sequoyah;

A261EF05F2BF4DA38E0E19BB801E8FAA.description:
explaining the role of broken treaties and the factors that led to military defeat of
Indigenous peoples, including, but not limited to the resistance of Indigenous nations
to encroachments and assimilation and the Trail of Tears;

59601C0B12A94FF59ED3E59AA6EA8D48.description:
examining founding documents to explore the development of American constitutional
government, with emphasis on the significance of the Virginia Declaration of Rights and
the Virginia Statute for Religious Freedom in the framing of the Bill of Rights;

38F21686FADA4BB0A4C4F3B307229692.description:
describing efforts by individuals and groups to mobilize support for the American
Revolution, including the Minutemen, the Sons of Liberty, the First and Second
Continental Congresses, and the Committees of Correspondence;

2625A365F38B4D5EABDE9DD652C677E2.description:
describing the cooperation that existed at times between the colonists and Indigenous
peoples during the 1600s and 1700s, including, but not limited to agriculture, the fur
trade, military alliances, treaties, and cultural interchanges;

826971568B2043E1B2446825D0E92A08.description:
describing the development of political self-government and a free-market economic
system, as well as the differences among the British, Spanish, and French colonial systems;
and

23B5CED647734B2496AC1A7652E10737.description:
describing the reasons for establishing colonies in North America and the individuals and
groups involved, including but not limited to John Smith, Roger Williams, William Penn,
Lord Baltimore, William Bradford, and John Winthrop;

97B82B4CA49545F7B322D604B0953A08.description:
describing the entrepreneurial characteristics of early explorers, including, but not limited
to Christopher Columbus, Francisco Vázquez de Coronado, and Ponce de León and the
technological developments that made nautical exploration possible;

D078CC8087B74A1DB27B9E694E396EED.description:
selecting and synthesizing evidence from information sources, including, but not limited to
artifacts, primary and secondary sources, charts, graphs, and diagrams, to question and
understand information about events in Virginia and United States history;
